courses.learning_outcomes:
At the end of the course, students are expected to:
- Understand the essence of spatial data modelling, spatial analysis skills, navigation and positioning techniques, latest development trends, GIS applications and project management;
- Gain experiences in investigating and solving real problems using GIS through practices and final project.

At the end of the course, students are expected to:
- Understand the principles of applying GIS to the areas of transportation and logistics;
- Gain familiarity with the use of GIS-T tools;
- Develop competence in implementing an application of GIS for transportation or logistics.

At the end of the course, students are expected to:
- Understand the principles of satellite remote sensing;
- Learn the techniques of digital image analysis;
- Understand how digital image analysis is being used in geographical studies.

At the end of the course, students are expected to:

- Understand the application of remote sensing data in different aspects of the environment including vegetation, urban landscape and water;
- Learn the skills in processing and analysing different types of remote sensing data;
- Extract initial statistics and thematic information from different data.

• Acquire advanced knowledge and skills in classification problems

At the end of the course, students are expected to:
- Master the GPS navigation and positioning techniques and the measures to improve the results;
- Understand how GNSS can be applied in various fields and the ways to resolve the relevant issues of application;
- Employ GPS receivers to collect the data for various geospatial applications.

The emphasis of this course is placed on the fundamentals of artificial intelligence methods for developing decision support systems and the hands-on experience in using and designing

decision support systems for smart-city management. After taking the course, students are expected to:

- Understand the basic concepts of artificial intelligence methods;

- Know the basic paradigms for knowledge representation and inference based on artificial intelligence methods;

- Use in-house spatial decision support system (SDSS) tool to develop simple SDSS.

At the end of the course, students are expected to:
- Develop an understanding of geospatial modeling and simulation methods;
- Evaluate the trade-offs among different modeling and simulation methods;
- Demonstrate a working knowledge to solve real-world geographical issues using the methods learned.

At the end of the course, students are expected to:
- Understand the principles of GIS Design using Structured System Analysis and Design Method;
- Gain familiarity with the methods for customizing GIS;
- Develop competence in implementing a GIS-based application system.

The master thesis requires a high degree of independent work as the student is working and guided by a supervisor.
Upon completion of the dissertation, students should be able to:
- Advance the knowledge and understanding of Geoinformation science on a variety of problems, with an analysis or application of geographical or spatial data;
- Demonstrate ability to select, design and implement an appropriate application topic in Geoinformation science through independent learning;
- Improve the skills on doing a project within a given time frame, applying scientific methodologies with constant critical analysis.

courses.course_syllabus:
A master thesis project should consist of the following moments.

1. Finding a suitable subject relevant to the program;

2. The finding of and coming to an agreement with your supervisor;

3. Setting up a final project-plan, time schedule;

4. Performing the research, collecting, analyzing and interpretation of data and results;

5. Writing the thesis (e.g. literature review, main body, conclusions);

6. Presentation and defending in the master thesis examination;

7. Finalizing and publishing the thesis.
